Part 1 - Theory¶

1.1 The invariant distribution of XtXt¶

Definition Consider a Markov Chain (Xt)t≥0(Xt)t≥0 with state space χ={1,2,...,n}χ={1,2,...,n} and transition matrix PP. The distribution π=(π1,π2,...,πn)∈Rnπ=(π1,π2,...,πn)∈Rn on χχ is a stationary distribution for (Xt)t≥0(Xt)t≥0 if: π=πPπ=πP

1.2 The limiting distribution of XtXt¶

Definition Consider a Markov Chain (Xt)t≥0(Xt)t≥0 with state space χ={1,2,...,n}χ={1,2,...,n} and transition matrix PP. The distribution π=(π1,π2,...,π|χ|)∈Rnπ=(π1,π2,...,π|χ|)∈Rn on χχ is the limiting distribution of (Xt)t≥0(Xt)t≥0 if: πj=limt→+∞Ptij∀i,j∈χπj=limt→+∞Pijt∀i,j∈χ

1.3 The asymptotic distribution of XtXt¶

Definition Consider a Markov Chain (Xt)t≥0(Xt)t≥0 with state space χ={1,2,...,n}χ={1,2,...,n} and transition matrix PP. The distribution π=(π1,π2,...,π|χ|)∈Rnπ=(π1,π2,...,π|χ|)∈Rn on χχ is the asymptotic distribution of (Xt)t≥0(Xt)t≥0 if: πj=limt→+∞visits of Xt to state j before time t given X0=it∀i,j∈χπj=limt→+∞visits of Xt to state j before time t given X0=it∀i,j∈χ

1.4 The Convergence Theorem¶

Theorem Consider a Markov Chain (Xt)t≥0(Xt)t≥0 with state space χχ and transition matrix PP. If χχ is finite, and XtXt is irreducible and aperiodic, then the unique stationary distribution ππ is also the limiting distribution of XtXt and the asymptotic distribution of XtXt.

This result allows us to pick the definition that we prefer in terms of computations required, and derive all three distributions at once.

Point 1 - Checking convergence theorem conditions¶

We have χ={1,2,3,4,5}χ={1,2,3,4,5}. Its transition matrix PP is:

P=⎛⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜⎝P11P12P13P14P15P21P22P23P24P25P31P32P33P34P35P41P42P43P44P45P51P52P53P54P55⎞⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟⎠=⎛⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜⎝01/31/31/300001010000001/201/200010⎞⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟⎠P=(P11P12P13P14P15P21P22P23P24P25P31P32P33P34P35P41P42P43P44P45P51P52P53P54P55)=(01/31/31/300001010000001/201/200010)

We immediately see that χχ is finite. We also see that XtXt is not periodic, as each state can be visited at irregular intervals. For what concerns irreducibility, we evaluate communicating states:

2←13←14←14←21←33←45←44←52←13←14←14←21←33←45←44←5

We determine the presence of 1 communicating class S⊆χS⊆χ. We have 1↔31↔3, and 3←43←4, so S={1,3,4}S={1,3,4} are communicating. But then 4↔54↔5, so 5∈S5∈S. Also, since 1←31←3 and 2←12←1, we see that 22 also communicates indirectly with 44 and 55. So 2∈S2∈S. We have proved that XtXt is irreducible, as all states communicate with each other.

XtXt meets the assumptions of the convergence theorem.

Point 2.3 - Computing the asymptotic distribution¶

In the spirit of what we verified earlier on the differences in the limiting distribution for different initial states, we also compute the asymptotic distribution for all possible beginning states. We then examine convergence of πasymptjπjasympt for j=1,2,...,5j=1,2,...,5 given initial state X0=1X0=1.

In [7]:
np.random.seed(123)

N = 100000
chi = [1,2,3,4,5]
pi_asympt = {f'freq.{n}': None for n in chi}

for X_0 in chi:
    
    X_past = X_0
    visits = [0,0,0,0,0]

    convergence_df_dict = {f'freq.{n}': np.zeros(N) for n in chi}
    convergence_df = pd.DataFrame(convergence_df_dict)
    
    for i in range(1,N):
        X_curr = np.random.choice(chi, p = P[X_past-1])  # we pick the right row of P for the probabilities
    
        visits[X_curr-1] = visits[X_curr-1] + 1
        convergence_df.iloc[i] = np.array(visits)/i
    
        X_past = X_curr

    pi_asympt['freq.'+str(X_0)] = np.array(visits)/N

To examine the convergence of the asymptotic distribution to the invariant distribution, we plot the simulated values of πasymptπasympt (which we will refer to as ^πasymptπ^asympt) against the number of iterations, and we compute backward-looking mean squared distances between πasymptπasympt and πinvπinv. More specifically, for every initial state i∈χi∈χ, we construct the following series MSD(i,t)=1tt∑k=1||^πasympt(i,k)−πinv(i)||2at every iteration t=1,2,...,N for starting state i∈χMSD(i,t)=1t∑k=1t||π^asympt(i,k)−πinv(i)||2at every iteration t=1,2,...,N for starting state i∈χ where:

  • ^πasympt(k)π^asympt(k) is the 5×55×5 estimated matrix of asymptotic distributions at iteration kk, and we pick its row ii when we choose a starting state X0=iX0=i.
  • πinv(i)πinv(i) is the ii-th element of the vector representing the invariant distribution (i.e. the invariant distribution's probability that Xt=iXt=i)

Essentially, at each iteration tt, for a given state ii, we sum together the distances between πinvπinv and the ^πasympt(t)π^asympt(t) estimated at all previous iteration. We then divide the sum by tt to get an average. This way, if ^πasymptπ^asympt converges to πinvπinv, we expect the measure to converge to zero. So for instance, if we choose starting state 11, at iteration 5, we have: MSD(i,t)=15[(^πasympt(i,1)−πinv(i))2+(^πasympt(i,2)−πinv(i))2+...+(^πasympt(i,5)−πinv(i))2]MSD(i,t)=15[(π^asympt(i,1)−πinv(i))2+(π^asympt(i,2)−πinv(i))2+...+(π^asympt(i,5)−πinv(i))2]

In [70]:
P2 = np.zeros((len(network.index),len(network.index)))
for X_curr in network.index:
    p = 1/sum(network.iloc[X_curr])
    
    for X_next in network.iloc[X_curr][network.iloc[X_curr] != 0].index:
        P2[X_curr, X_next] = p
        
    assert round(sum(P2[X_curr]),10) == 1, "Sum not equal to 1 for index"+str(X_next)  
    # we round to 10 digits to avoid unnecessary errors (e.g. 0.999999999999998 != 1)

It's not only evident that the distributions are different: we can also see that there are two clusters of probability in the PP matrix. Starting from the low-numbered ranks within the state space, it's impossible to reach the high-numbered ranks. This is because the Markov Chain is not irreducible, since there are two distinct communicating classes. The convergence theorem does not apply. Moreover, because of reducibility, the stationary distribution of XtXt is not unique.

Point 3.3 - The Modified Pagerank Algorithm¶

We define a second transition probability matrix P∗P∗ as follows, given a parameter αα that we set to 0.950.95.

P∗=αPij+(1−α)1n∀i,j∈χP∗=αPij+(1−α)1n∀i,j∈χ

In [84]:
alpha = 0.95
n = 50

P2_star = alpha * P2 + (1-alpha) * 1/n

Things now change radically. We now have P∗ij>0∀i,jPij∗>0∀i,j, so the markov chain associated with XtXt is irreducible, and the convergence theorem applies.

np.random.seed(123)

X0 = [1,10,20,30,40,50]
N = 10000
asympt_star = {}

for X0_value in X0:
    visits = np.zeros(50)

    convergence_df_dict = {f"freq.{n}": None for n in range(1, 51)}

    convergence_df = pd.DataFrame(convergence_df_dict, index = np.array(list(range(1,51))))

    for i in range(1,N):
